external_knowledge:
- 'Fall 2022' refers to a specific academic semester;
- 'scholars' refers to students;
- 'harvested' is used metaphorically to describe the achievement or earning of grades.

- "blossoming scholars" refers to students who have active enrollment status and have completed at least one assignment with a non-null score;
- "thrive" and "flourishing grades" refer to students with an average assignment score greater than 60;
- "not let any assignment wilt" means that the students have scores for all their assignments, i.e., no null scores.

- "cumulative wisdom" refers to the cumulative average score of students in each department;
- "intellectual fruits" refers to the average scores achieved by students in each course;
- "faculty" refers to the department to which students belong.

- "blossomed with more than one student" refers to departments with more than one student;
- "count of their blossoms" refers to the total number of students in each department;
- "average sunlight they receive" refers to the average attendance rate of students in each department.

- "stars of the academic firmament" refers to top-performing students;
- "brightness in assignments" refers to high average assignment scores;
- "illuminated their courses" means they have performed well in their assignments.
